One way to integrate f(x) = e^(-x^2/2) using Monte Carlo integration is to generate random points within the region of integration, and use the function to evaluate the points. The average value of the function at these points can then be used as an estimate of the definite integral.

Here is an example of how this could be implemented in C++:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <cstdlib>
#include <cmath>

double f(double x) {
    // function to integrate
    return exp(-x*x/2);
}

double monte_carlo_integration(double a, double b, int n) {
    double total = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        double x = ((double)rand() / RAND_MAX) * (b - a) + a;
        total += f(x);
    }
    double estimate = total / n * (b - a);
    return estimate;
}

int main() {
    double a = -3; // lower bound
    double b = 3; // upper bound
    int n = 10000; // number of random points
    double estimate = monte_carlo_integration(a, b, n);
    std::cout << "Estimate of the definite integral of f(x) from " << a << " to " << b << ": " << estimate << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```
This code will approximate the definite integral of f(x) = e^(-x^2/2) from -3 to 3 using 10000 random points.

Please note that this is not the exact integral of the function because the monte carlo integration is an approximation method. The error in the approximation will decrease as the number of samples increases.
